Human population with swap

Daphné Giorgi

Sarah Kaakaï

Vincent Lemaire

Source: vignettes/IBMPopSim-human_popIMD.Rmd
IBMPopSim-human_popIMD.Rmd

VOIR SI ON MET DES MIGRATIONS EXTERNES

This vignette provides an example of population simulation with the package IBMPopSim, for simulating a “human population” based on data from England and Wales (EW) population, and where individuals are characterized by the so-called Index of Multiple Deprivation (IMD), a deprivation index based on the place of living mettre des références.

A toy model is simulated, where the individuals’ demographic rates depend on their IMD. Due to internal migrations, individuals can change of IMD over their life course (swap events), and the model also include external migrations (entry events).

As this a more advance example of IBM simulation with IBMPopSim, it is recommanded to start by reading the vignettes descriptions + human pop.

Example description

The population is structured by age, gender and IMD. The population is distributed into five IMD quintiles. Group 1 corresponds to the least deprived subpopulation, and group 5 to the most deprived subpopulation.

Death and birth intensity are constant over time, but depend on the individuals age, gender and IMD. For instance, individuals in group 5 have a higher death intensity than individuals in group 1.

Individuals inherit the same IMD than their parent at birth, but can change of IMD over time, due to internal migration. In this toy model, we assume than younger individuals around 20 are more likely to move to more a deprived neighbourhood, while individivals in the age class 30-45 are more likely to move to a less deprived neighbourhood ( ref ).

Population creation

The inital population is a 100 000 individuals population sampled from England and Wales’ 2014 age pyramid, structured by single year of age, gender and IMD quintile (source: Office for National Statistics).

The population_from_population function creates a population of size pop_size based on an starting population.

Events description

There are 3 possible types of events :

  • Birth
  • Death
  • Swap (internal migrations)
  • MIGRATIONS EXTERNES?

Each event is caracterised by its intensity and its kernel, as follows.

Death events

Individuals can die with an intensity depending on their age, gender and IMD subgroup (they are no interactions). For each gender \(\epsilon\) and IMD subgroup \(i=1..5\), we introduce a step function

\[d_i^\epsilon (a), \quad a=0,..a_{max}\]

defining the death intensity of an individual of age \(a\), gender \(\epsilon\) and subgroup \(i\).

Parameters

Death intensity are based on EW 2014 age specific death rates by gender and IMD (source: Office for National Statistics).

Death rates are lower in less deprived quintiles.

ggplot(EW_popIMD_14$death_rates$male, aes(x=age,y=log(value),color=factor(IMD)))+geom_step()+
scale_color_discrete(name="IMD quintile")+ylab("Males log death rates")

Step functions creation

The death intensity functions for each IMD and gender are defined as parameters of the model, as two list of R step functions.

These parameters will be transformed in C++ in a vector of functions (starting from index 0).

params_death = with(EW_popIMD_14$death_rates,
    list(
        "death_male" = lapply(1:5, function(i) stepfun(x= subset(male, IMD==i)[,"age"], y= c(0,subset(male, IMD==i)[,"value"]))),
        "death_female" = lapply(1:5, function(i) stepfun(x= subset(female, IMD==i)[,"age"], y= c(0,subset(female, IMD==i)[,"value"])))

    )
)

C++ code chunk implementing the intensity of a death event:

intensity_code_death <- '
    if (I.male)
        result = death_male[(I.IMD-1)](age(I,t)); 
    else
        result = death_female[(I.IMD-1)](age(I,t));
'

Creation of the event

By default, the name of the event is “death”.

death_event <- mk_event_individual(
    type = "death",
    intensity_code = intensity_code_death
)

Birth events

In this toy model, only women give birth, with and Weibull shaped intensity \(b_i(a)\) depending on their age \(a\) and IMD subgroup \(i\),

\[b_i(a)=TFR_i\frac{\beta_i}{\alpha_i}(\frac{(a-\bar{a})}{\alpha_i})^{\beta_i-1}\exp((−\frac{a-\bar{a}}{\alpha_i})^{\beta_i}).\]

These functions can be implemented by using the IBMPopSim function weibull(k,c), which creates an R function corresponding the Weibull density function with parameters \((k,c)\), and which is translated as a C++ function during the model creation.

By default, the newborn inherit the IMD of his parent.

Parameters

We consider that women in the IMD subgroup 1 and 2 (resp. 4 and 5) have the same birth intensity functions. The parameters for birth events are thus composed of 10 parameters:

  • \(\bar{a}\)
  • \(\alpha=(\alpha_1,\alpha_2,\alpha_3)\)
  • \(\beta=(\beta_1,\beta_2,\beta_3)\)
  • \(TFR = (TFR_1,TFR_2, TFR_3)\).

Parameters values are available in toy_params$birth.

# birth_sex_ratio = 1.05
params_birth <- with(toy_params$birth,
    list(
        "TFR_weights" = TFR_weights,
        "a_mean"= 15,
        "birth" =     list(
            weibull(beta[1], alpha[1]), # Weibull functions creation 
            weibull(beta[2], alpha[2]),
            weibull(beta[3], alpha[3])),
        "p_male" = 0.51 # probability to give birth to a male
    )
)
plot(x=0:50,y= params_birth$TFR_weight[[1]]*params_birth$birth[[1]](0:50-params_birth$a_mean), type="l", xlab= "age", ylab="birth intensity", col="green",ylim = c(0,0.16), main="Birth intensities" )
lines(x=0:50,y= params_birth$TFR_weight[[2]]*params_birth$birth[[2]](0:50-params_birth$a_mean),col = "red")
lines(x=0:50,y= params_birth$TFR_weight[[3]]*params_birth$birth[[3]](0:50-params_birth$a_mean),col = "blue")
legend("topright", col= c("green","red","blue") ,legend =c("IMD 1 and 2", "IMD 3", "IMD 4 and 5"),bty = "n", lwd="2")

Event creation

C++ code implementing the intensity of a birth event. The lists params_birth$birth and TFR_weights are then tranformed into C++ vectors (index starting at 0).

birth_intensity_code <- '
    if (I.male) result = 0.;
    else {
        if (I.IMD <= 2) result = TFR_weights[0] * birth[0](age(I,t)-a_mean);
        if (I.IMD == 3) result = TFR_weights[1] * birth[1](age(I,t)-a_mean);
        if (I.IMD >= 4) result = TFR_weights[2] * birth[2](age(I,t)-a_mean);
    }
'

Birth event creation

birth_event <- mk_event_individual(
    type = "birth",
    intensity_code = birth_intensity_code,
    kernel_code = "newI.male = CUnif(0, 1) < p_male;" # Choice of gender for newborn 
)

Swap event

Individuals can move during their lifetime, and thus change of IMD subgroup (swap events).

We assume that an individual can change of IMD subgroup with an intensity depending on his age and IMD subgroup.

Young individuals in the age class \([15,30]\) and in the less deprived IMD quintiles (1 and 2) can move too more deprived areas, for instance for studying. On the other hand, older individuals in the age class \([30,45]\) and \([0,15]\), and in deprived areas can move to a less deprived area, modelling for instance family formation, moving out to less deprived areas.

Age-specific swap intensities are given by 5 step functions, one for each IMD subgroup. When a swap event occur, the new IMD subgroup of the individual is determined by a discrete random variable depending on his age.

Parameters

Example parameters values are given in toy_params$swap.

Swap intensity are saved as model parameters as a list of step functions, which will be transformed into a C++ vector of functions when the model is created. The vectors of discrete probabilities determining the action of the event when a swap occur is saved in a matrix, which will be transformed into a Rcpp Armadillo matrix.

Note that data frame are not accepted as model parameters.

params_swap <- with(toy_params$swap,
    list(
        "swap_intensities" = apply(intensities, 2, function(rates) stepfun(x=ages, y=20*rates)),
        "swap_distribution" = as.matrix(distribution),
        "swap_age_to_idx" = stepfun(ages, seq(0,3))
    )
)

J’augmente l’intensité des swaps pour voir leur effet"

params_swap$swap_intensities[[4]] <- stepfun(x=toy_params$swap$ages, y=200*toy_params$swap$intensities[[4]])
params_swap$swap_intensities[[5]] <- stepfun(x=toy_params$swap$ages, y=200*toy_params$swap$intensities[[5]])
 df_intensities <- melt(data.frame("age"=c(0,15,30,45),toy_params$swap$intensities),id.vars="age")
ggplot(df_intensities, aes(x=age,y=value,color=variable))+geom_step()+
scale_color_discrete(name="Origin IMD quintile")+ylab("swap intensity")

C++ code of the intensity of a swap event, using the model parameters:

intensity_code_swap <- '
    result = swap_intensities[I.IMD-1](age(I,t));
'

C++ kernel code of a swap event

If a swap event occurs, the new IMD subgroup of the individual is determined by a discrete random variables, with probability distribution given by a row a params_swap$swap_distribution, depending on his age.

For instance, an individual of age in \([0,15]\) has a probability of 0.66 to move on IMD subgroup 1 and 0.34 to move to IMD subgroup 2.

Discrete random variables can be drawn in IBMPopSim by calling the function Cdiscrete in the kernel code, with an Armadillo vector or matrix ( see vignette description).

params_swap$swap_distribution
##           IMD1      IMD2      IMD3      IMD4      IMD5
## [1,] 0.6562743 0.3437257 0.0000000 0.0000000 0.0000000
## [2,] 0.0000000 0.0000000 0.1318681 0.6268572 0.2412746
## [3,] 0.6562743 0.3437257 0.0000000 0.0000000 0.0000000
kernel_code_swap <- '
    int idx = swap_age_to_idx(age(I,t)); // variables must by typed in C++
    I.IMD = CDiscrete(swap_distribution.begin_row(idx),
                      swap_distribution.end_row(idx)) + 1;
'

Swap event creation:

swap_event <- mk_event_individual(
    type = "swap",
    intensity_code = intensity_code_swap,
    kernel_code = kernel_code_swap
)

Model creation (without id)

The model is created by calling the function mk_model with as arguments:

  • The individuals’ characteristics.
  • The events list.
  • The vector of model parameters (only parameters name and types are saved).
params = c(params_birth, params_death, params_swap)
model <- mk_model(
    characteristics = get_characteristics(EW_popIMD_14$sample),
    events = list(birth_event, death_event, swap_event),
    parameters = params)

summary(model)

Simulation

Events bounds

The first step before simulating the model is to compute bounds for each event intensity.

Birth intensity bound

E <-c(0,50)
birth_max <- with(params,
                  max(sapply(1:3, function(i)(
                      TFR_weights[i]* optimize(f= birth[[i]], interval =E , maximum=TRUE)$objective)))
                  )

Death intensity bound

The operator max has been overloaded in IBMPopSim and can be applied to step functions.

death_max <- max(sapply(params$death_male, max),
                 sapply(params$death_female, max))

Swap intensity bound

swap_max <- max(sapply(params$swap_intensities, max))

Simulation

Recording all swap events is computationnaly expensive. To overcome this difficulty, the simulation in the presence of swap events returns a list of data frame, composed of a “picture” of the population at all times in the vector argument time of popsim (see vignette description for more details)

The first component of the variable t_sim below is the initial time. The simulation returns n-1 data frame representing the population at \(t\_sim[1],..,t\_sim[n]\). The data frame corresponding to time \(t\_sim[i]\) is composed of all individuals who lived in the population before \(t\_sim[i]\), with their characteristics at time \(t\_sim[i]\).

t_sim <- 0:100
n <- length(t_sim)
sim_out <- popsim(model,
    population = EW_popIMD_14$sample, # Initial population 
    events_bounds = c('birth' = birth_max, 'swap' = swap_max, 'death' = death_max), # Names corresponding to events name
    parameters = params,
    time = t_sim,
    multithreading=TRUE# Set to T since there are no interactions
                 )

Outputs

Population after 20 years of simulation

p <- sim_out$population[[20]]
pyr_IMD <-  age_pyramid(p, time = 20,ages = c(0:110,130))
plot_pyramid(pyr_IMD)

Remarque The high number of individuals aged over 100 is due to the fact that mortality rates are assumed to be constant at ages over 90, which is of course not realistic for human populations (see Vignette human pop) for another choice of moratlity rates.

Age pyramid with different IMD subgroups

pyr_IMD$group_name <- with(pyr_IMD, ifelse(male, paste('Males - IMD', IMD), paste('Females - IMD', IMD)))
colors <- c(sequential_hcl(n=5, palette = "Magenta"),
            sequential_hcl(n=5, palette = "Teal"))
names(colors) <- c(paste('Females - IMD', 1:5),
                   paste('Males - IMD', 1:5))
# note that you must have setequal(names(colors), pyr_IMD$name) is TRUE
plot_pyramid(pyr_IMD, colors)

Evolution of population composition by age group

age_pyrs <- lapply(1:(n-1), function (i)(age_pyramid(sim_out$population[[i]],t_sim[i+1],seq(20,40,10))))
age_pyr_fem <- filter(bind_rows(age_pyrs,.id="time"), male==FALSE)
compo_pop_fem <- age_pyr_fem%>% group_by(age,time)%>% mutate(perc = value/sum(value))
ggplot(compo_pop_fem, aes(x=as.integer(time),y=perc,colour=as.factor(IMD)))+
geom_line()+
facet_wrap(~age)+
scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)

Different simulations

Deactivate swap events

Quand on désactive les morts ça désactive en fait les swaps, et inversement. Je n’arrive pas à voir d’où ça vient

sim_out_noswp <- popsim(model,
    population = EW_popIMD_14$sample, # Initial population 
    events_bounds = c('birth' = birth_max, 'swap' = 0, 'death' = death_max), # Names corresponding to events name
    parameters = params,
    time = t_sim,
    multithreading=TRUE, # Set to T since there are no interactions
    seed = sim_out$arguments$seed)
